source: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipes/roasted-butternut-tagine-5a7ffdd0ae08b5794e17c5e2
course: main course
servings: 2
---

Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C. Remove the top from the @butternut squash{1}(peeled), halve lengthways, remove the seeds, then cut into 1cm wide slices. Chop into 1cm chunks. Pop the squash onto a #baking tray{} and drizzle over some oil, a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch}. Roast in your oven until crispy on the outside and soft in the middle, ~{25-30%minutes}.

Pour the @water{for the bulgur} into a #saucepan{} on medium high heat and add half the @vegetable stock pot{1%half}. Stir together to dissolve the stock pot. Once boiling, add the @bulgur wheat{100%g} and bring back to the boil. Cover with a #lid{}, remove from the heat and leave to the side until everything else is cooked.

Meanwhile, remove the ends from the @courgette{1}, quarter lengthways, then chop into 1cm chunks. Finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{1/2%for stirring}(stalks and all). Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1} in a #colander{}.

Heat a #frying pan{} on medium high heat (no oil!). Add the courgette with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch}. Dry fry until slightly browned, ~{4-5%minutes}. Turn the heat to medium, add a splash of @oil{} and the @chermoula spice mix{1}, stir together and cook for ~{1%minute} more. Pour in the @finely chopped tomatoes with onion and garlic{1} and the @water{for the tagine}, and stir in the remaining @vegetable stock pot{1%half}.

Add in the chickpeas and @raisins{40}, and bring the mixture to the boil, then reduce the heat and simmer until thick and tomatoey, about ~{10%minutes}. Once the squash is cooked, stir it into the tagine as well. When it's done, taste and add salt and pepper if you feel it needs it.

> Add a splash of water if it's looking a bit dry.

Once everything is ready, fluff up the bulgur, taste and add salt and pepper if required. Stir in the remaining parsley. Serve the bulgur with the tagine on top and a spoonful of @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%g}. Sprinkle over the remaining parsley and the @dukkah mix{1}. Enjoy!